. Something hit me from something you said about @delba's implementation that might simplify everything. How about just adding this convenience init to DefaultKeys:
```
public class DefaultsKey: DefaultsKeys {
    public let _key: String
public init(_ key: String) {
    self._key = key
}

public convenience init(_ key: String, _ defaultValue: ValueType) {
    self.init(key)

    if !Defaults.hasKey(key) {
        Defaults[key] = defaultValue
    }
}

}
```
That's all the code update we need since all it's doing is storing the value into NSUserDefaults. And because the value is persisted first thing, everything after in SwiftyUserDefaults follows the natural flow as it did before without further code changes needed.
What I like about this is there is no race conditions introduced and the code change is super minimal. Also, a big benefit is all defaults are packaged in the declaration of the DefaultKeys in one place. It would look like this:
extension DefaultsKeys {
    public static let someString1 = DefaultsKey<String>("SomeString1")
    static let someString2 = DefaultsKey<String>("SomeString2", "abc") // default added
    static let someNumber1 = DefaultsKey<Int>("SomeNumber1")
    static let someNumber2 = DefaultsKey<Int>("SomeNumber2", 888) // default added
    static let someBool1 = DefaultsKey<Bool>("SomeBool1")
    static let someBool2 = DefaultsKey<Bool>("SomeBool2", true)
    static let someDate1 = DefaultsKey<NSDate>("SomeDate1")
    static let someDate2 = DefaultsKey<NSDate>("SomeDate2", NSDate()) // default added
}
The only thing we'd have to resolve is the suiteName situation since this is under the assumption that Defaults should always be NSUserDefaults.standardUserDefaults(). But this is another topic that is ongoing in another thread.
. I had a break-thru in regards to this discussion that I'd like to document here. Apparently, the best place to register defaults is indeed in AppDelegate.init:
```
@UIApplicationMain
class AppDelegate: UIResponder, UIApplicationDelegate {
    var window: UIWindow?
override init() {
    super.init()
    Defaults.registerDefaults([
        "userName": "radex",
        "launchCount": 10
    ])
}

func application(application: UIApplication, didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions: [NSObject: AnyObject]?) -> Bool {
      ...
}

}
```
Note that the native registerDefaults function will register the values to your UserDefaults for the entire lifecycle of your app; it will not persist to it. Once your app terminates and start up again in the future, those values will not be in your UserDefaults anymore unless you keep registering the defaults in the beginning of your app (or before you need them).
