humblehacker:
Thanks for the feedback.  I need to compose from two values because the back-end system where these values originate from can only handle primitive types, and trying to enforce a particular format strictly by convention could be error-prone.
I'm not completely sold on this solution however, since it's currently limited to types composed of values of a single type, and the order of the contained values is not enforced (too easy to accidentally swap width and height. I'm investigating solutions, and welcome any ideas.
. I'm thinking now that this is a case of premature generalization.  Explicit key classes take up just as much code and are safer to deal with.  Example:
```
extension DefaultsKeys
{
    public static let mapRegion = MKCoordinateRegionDefaultsKey(lat: "mapLatitude", long: "mapLongitude", latDelta: "mapLatitudeDelta", longDelta: "mapLongitudeDelta")
}
public
class MKCoordinateRegionDefaultsKey: DefaultsKeys
{
    public let _centerLongitudeKey: DefaultsKey
    public let _centerLatitudeKey:  DefaultsKey
    public let _spanLongitudeKey:   DefaultsKey
    public let _spanLatitudeKey:    DefaultsKey
public
init(lat: String, long: String, latDelta: String, longDelta: String)
{
    _centerLatitudeKey  = DefaultsKey<CLLocationDegrees>(lat)
    _centerLongitudeKey = DefaultsKey<CLLocationDegrees>(long)
    _spanLatitudeKey    = DefaultsKey<CLLocationDegrees>(latDelta)
    _spanLongitudeKey   = DefaultsKey<CLLocationDegrees>(longDelta)
}

}
public
extension NSUserDefaults
{
    public
    subscript(key: MKCoordinateRegionDefaultsKey) -> MKCoordinateRegion
    {
        get
        {
            var region = MKCoordinateRegion()
            region.center.latitude     = self[ key._centerLatitudeKey ]
            region.center.longitude    = self[ key._centerLongitudeKey ]
            region.span.latitudeDelta  = self[ key._spanLatitudeKey ]
            region.span.longitudeDelta = self[ key._spanLongitudeKey ]
            return region
        }
        set
        {
            self[key._centerLatitudeKey] = newValue.center.latitude
            self[key._centerLongitudeKey] = newValue.center.longitude
            self[key._spanLatitudeKey] = newValue.span.latitudeDelta
            self[key._spanLongitudeKey] = newValue.span.longitudeDelta
        }
    }
}
```
Unfortunately, this fails to compile outside of SwiftyUserDefaults.swift because the DefaultsKeys initializer is private.
Can we lift that restriction? Or can you think of another way to work around it?
